Title: Buster the Noodle Head Dog Goes to Bed
Credit: Written by
Author: Debra McGuinty
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/25/2025
Notes: Warm stylized children's-picture-book live action; soft practical light; one consistent medium throughout. Buster is a small black-and-white dog, bright-eyed and bouncy, not very bright, with a soft "noodle head" look. Momma and Daddy are gentle parents in cozy home clothes. Buster's black-and-white pajamas stay on once he wears them.

FADE IN:

EXT. BACKYARD - DAY

A sunny little yard. BUSTER, a small black-and-white dog, rockets across the grass, jumping around like a frog—springy, silly, full of joy.

NARRATOR
He's Buster the Noodle Head Dog.
He jumps around like a frog.
He's small, black, and white—
but not very bright!
He's Buster the Noodle Head Dog.

Buster skids, tumbles, pops up grinning, tail a blur.

INT. LIVING ROOM - EVENING

Cozy home. Lamps glow. MOMMA stands near the hallway, kind but firm. Buster trots in, still buzzing with energy.

MOMMA
It's time for bed.

Buster's ears perk. He wants to rest his furry head—but first he circles the rug, sniffs the floor, considers a very bad idea.

NARRATOR
Before he goes, he has to potty.
Going on the floor is naughty!

Momma points toward the door.

MOMMA
A doggy goes outside.

Buster cocks his head. The idea does not compute.

NARRATOR
That makes no sense in Buster's head!

He stares at the floor. Stares at Momma. Stares at the door. Then—off he goes.

EXT. BACKYARD - EVENING

Dusk. Bushes along the fence. Buster walks around, sniffs, finds his spot among the bushes, and does his job like a good (if noodle-headed) dog.

He bolts back toward the house, proud.

INT. LIVING ROOM - EVENING

Buster bursts in and does a little spin for Momma—show-off twirl, paws tapping.

NARRATOR
For Mom he does a little spin.

He spins again, eyes on the treat jar.

NARRATOR
He spins around to get a treat.

Momma smiles, gently lays a treat by his feet. Buster gobbles it up.

He pads to his water bowl and has his drink of water too—loud, happy laps.

NARRATOR
This also would be good for you!

INT. HALLWAY / BOTTOM OF STAIRS - NIGHT

Momma holds up small black-and-white pajamas. Buster wriggles into them—same black-and-white pattern as his fur, now snug pajama top and bottoms.

NARRATOR
Pajamas, black and white he wears.

Pajama-clad Buster faces the staircase. Many stairs. He climbs—hop, scramble, hop—up toward Mom and Daddy's room.

NARRATOR
And then he climbs the many stairs
to get to Mom and Daddy's room.

INT. MOM AND DADDY'S ROOM - NIGHT

Soft lamp light. HOME SWEET HOME warmth: big bed, pillows, DADDY already settled under the covers. Momma turns down the blanket.

Buster reaches the top, gathers himself—and JUMPS into bed, none too soon, landing in a happy heap between them.

NARRATOR
And jump in bed, and none too soon.

Buster burrows, sighs, eyes growing heavy. Soft dreamy light plays over his face.

NARRATOR
He's not that smart, but still he knows
he'll have a dream of fluffy snows,
or bunnies running 'cross the yard—
and how he'll chase them very hard.

DREAM - EXT. SNOWY YARD - DAY (DREAM)

Fluffy snow. Buster bounds through white powder, then chases bunnies racing across a green yard—full speed, pure joy—until the dream softens back to dark.

INT. MOM AND DADDY'S ROOM - NIGHT

Buster settles deeper into the covers, warm and soft and quite well-fed.

NARRATOR
He goes to sleep because they say
tomorrow is another day.
Another day for silly dogs
to run and play and jump like frogs.

He falls asleep, lays down his head. Momma gently pets him while he sleeps.

NARRATOR
His Mommy pets him while he sleeps.
This noodle head is loved for keeps.

Buster snore-breathes. A tiny smile. Peaceful room.

NARRATOR
(whisper)
zzzzzzzzZ

FADE OUT.

THE END
